    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "Escrow accounts are typically held in a separate, insured trust account at a bank or trust company, which means the funds are legally segregated from the lawyer's operating accounts and personal assets. This separation ensures that even if the lawyer runs into financial trouble or attempts to mishandle the money, the escrow funds remain secure and accessible only for the specific transaction. If there is a delay, the escrow agent simply holds the funds in this safe vault until the conditions are met, and if the paperwork gets held up, the agent can't touch the money until the official release instructions are signed by all parties.\n\nTo add to that, if you suspect any tampering or fraud, you can immediately contact the Law Society of Ontario or the escrow company directly, as they are required to maintain strict audit trails for every dollar moving in and out of the account. This system is so robust that it's virtually impossible for funds to be stolen without leaving a paper trail that would be investigated by regulators. You can be confident that your money is locked in a digital and physical fortress that only opens when the deal is legally finalized.\n\nIt's worth noting that if a lawyer were to try and steal from an escrow account, they would face severe criminal charges",
